text:
DEAR MISS MANNERS: A very long time ago, my husband and I were invited to dinner at a restaurant by a colleague of his. I had not met the colleague or his wife prior to the dinner.  The men promised they wouldn’t talk shop, but they did -- throughout the entire meal. There was no inclusion of us women. I tried to initiate a conversation with the wife, and she shut me down immediately with something along the lines of, “I’d rather listen to what the men are talking about.” Gobsmacked, I just shrank back in the seat and ate my dinner. As my husband and I were leaving, I told him what had happened and he (rightfully) said that we’d never do that again. I should have gotten over this by now, but I fantasize about having left the table in some way. What should I have done? I didn’t want to be rude myself. GENTLE READER: Are you talking about a very, VERY long time ago? Because Miss Manners remembers those days -- when wives, if invited at all, were treated as table decorations to be talked around.  But didn’t we have a successful rebellion against that?  Apparently not successful enough, if it is now a wife who treats her guest like that. She need only have said, apologetically, “Sorry, I’m listening to them.” There is no need for you to fantasize about reacting effectively, and yet not rudely, because you already did: first by your silence, and then by your and your husband’s resolving never to socialize with them again.  *** (Please send your questions to Miss Manners at her website,
www.missmanners.com
; to her email,
dearmissmanners@gmail.com
; or through postal mail to Miss Manners, Andrews McMeel Syndication, 1130 Walnut St., Kansas City, MO 64106.)

metadata.title: Miss Manners: I tried to talk to her but she said, ‘I’d rather listen to what the men are talking about’

text:
TORONTO
—
J.C. Escarra
feels personally responsible for the
Yankees’ 12-5 loss
to the Blue Jays on Tuesday, a game-changing catcher’s interference on a check swing. Yankees
manager Aaron Boone blamed the mistake on a rule that he feels MLB ought to change. Reliever Luke Weaver, who allowed five seventh-inning rules immediately after the E2, agrees with his skipper. With two on and one out in the seventh inning of a tie game, the rookie catcher knows that he was too aggressive trying to frame a 3-2 fastball from Luke Weaver that already was a framed strike. Plate umpire Doug Eddings rung up pinch-hitter Addison Barger, but while checking his swing his bat clipped Escarra’s catcher’s mitt. The Blue Jays asked for replay challenge to overturn the strikeout, won and wound up with the bases loaded and one out instead of two on with two down when Escarra was charged with a second catcher’s interference call in two days. “It’s on me,” Escarra said. “I intend to get as close as possible, but obviously not letting that happen. I was too close. I didn’t help my team win today … or yesterday. “It shouldn’t happen, but it’s something I can control. I was just too deep in there trying to steal that strike.” Boone says the Yankees relentlessly prepare to avoid catcher’s interference by knowing which hitters are more prone to hitting a catcher’s mitt with a swing during framing situations. “We’re incredibly diligent on trying to eliminate that as much as possible,” Boone said. “I don’t know how many times it’s happened to us this year in the first three months. “It is something that we lean into every hitter. Who are we vulnerable with? Who are we not? We’ve met and we do that accordingly with our catchers.” What bothered Boone is that this one occurred when Barger didn’t even swing. “We benefited from a check swing last year,” Boone said. “I forget the game, but there should probably be something looked into that where a check swing can’t get you beat like that.” Weaver feels the same. “It’s pretty devastating, honestly,” he said. “I feel like that’s a really unfortunate part of our game. I don’t really personally think that belongs in our game. I think there should be some type of discretion to it. “I understand that there are moments where it’s very egregious and (batters) hit the glove on a full swing, but you feel like you earned something there and it was taken from you and it’s out of my control at that point. “Just a real silly thing to happen.” After it happened, the floodgates opened with the tie-breaking hit by Clement and then the grand slam by Springer, who had a great day going 3-for-4 with two homers and seven RBI. “I’m trying to get the groundball on the next pitch (to Clement) and it just finds the hole, then you run into a bad pitch there a guy that’s having a nice day and the game gets away from you.” The Blue Jays taking over the game after the catcher’s interference sickened Escarra. “Exactly,” he said. “It gave them bases loaded and the big hit came. I could have prevented it, so it was in my control.” Yankees -1.5 runline is +128 on
DraftKings
for Wednesday’s game against the Blue Jays. Our comprehensive
DraftKings Sportsbook review
will show you how to sign up and get started. Escarra says that he’s never had a problem with catcher’s interference calls until the last two days. “No,” he said. “It’s just trying to get the glove in the zone. If the pitch is out of the zone, I’m just trying to move it as fast as possible up and forward to steal that strike, to make it look like a strike to the umpire. “He wasn’t going to swing, but at the end of the day I shouldn’t have been too close like that. “Going forward, I’ve really got to make it a priority to not get in too deep in there.” Thank you for relying on us to provide the journalism you can trust. Please consider supporting us with a subscription. Randy Miller may be reached at
rmiller@njadvancemedia.com
.

metadata.title: Yankees lobby for rule change after game-changing catcher’s interference on check swing
